{"data":{"wordpressPost":{"title":"Agra: The Fort","content":"<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">It was 2002. That&#8217;s when we first went on a long trip (before that, my memory was more volatile than it is now, so I don&#8217;t remember where we went before that). And that was when we had first visited Agra. But I only have faint memories of Taj Mahal from that trip.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Last year, although I yearned for mountains, Agra was something I was interested in exploring, especially for taking photos of the Taj Mahal from a certain location that my mother had told me about ðŸ™‚</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><!--more--></p>\n<h1 style=\"text-align:justify;\">Day 3: 2nd November, 2015</h1>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">We travelled to Agra from Delhi via road.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Agra is an older city. Its age is reflected by its road patterns and its buildings.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Our hotel reservations had been done by one of my uncles, and the hotel was situated a kilometre away from the Taj! It was a bit isolated from the city and hence quieter and cooler.Â The four of us had lunch and then went to Agra Fort.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><img data-attachment-id=\"1912\" data-permalink=\"https://nabhoneelparchments.wordpress.com/2016/02/04/agra-the-fort/2nd-november-1-of-14/\" data-orig-file=\"https://nabhoneelparchments.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/2nd-november-1-of-14.jpg?w=1920&#038;h=585\" data-orig-size=\"1920,585\" data-comments-opened=\"1\" data-image-meta=\"{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;4&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;Nabhoneel Majumdar&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1446482876&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;24&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;800&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.0005&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}\" data-image-title=\"2nd November (1 of 14)\" data-image-description=\"\" data-medium-file=\"https://nabhoneelparchments.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/2nd-november-1-of-14.jpg?w=1920&#038;h=585?w=450\" data-large-file=\"https://nabhoneelparchments.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/2nd-november-1-of-14.jpg?w=1920&#038;h=585?w=700\" class=\" size-full wp-image-1912 aligncenter\" src=\"https://nabhoneelparchments.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/2nd-november-1-of-14.jpg?w=1920&#038;h=585\" alt=\"2nd November (1 of 14).jpg\" width=\"1920\" height=\"585\" srcset=\"https://nabhoneelparchments.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/2nd-november-1-of-14.jpg 1920w, https://nabhoneelparchments.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/2nd-november-1-of-14.jpg?w=150&amp;h=46 150w, https://nabhoneelparchments.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/2nd-november-1-of-14.jpg?w=450&amp;h=137 450w, https://nabhoneelparchments.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/2nd-november-1-of-14.jpg?w=768&amp;h=234 768w, https://nabhoneelparchments.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/2nd-november-1-of-14.jpg?w=700&amp;h=213 700w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" /></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">We decided to opt for an audio guide machine for the first time.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">An audio guide is an audio device. Places are numbered throughout a heritage site (with numbered boards) and if you type in the number on your device, a pre-recorded voice narrates various facts about that specific place. This is an amazing way of navigating your way through a heritage site, especially since there are audio effectsÂ to make your visit more realistic and notable.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">[This is something from Incredible India &#8211;Â <a href=\"http://www.audiocompass.in/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">audiocompass</a>Â &#8211; that I later found out]</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\">Agra fort isÂ <em>huge. </em>It&#8217;s more of like a city with walls.Â In fact, one <em>canÂ </em>get lost after a certain 